<a name='hTileMaps'></a>
>> Tilemaps
>>> Endless maps
For something like an endless runner game, have a look at this script to see how you can approach this: [[./data/fantomCX/examples/TileMaps/EndlessMap/EndlessMap.cxs|EndlessMap.cxs]].

>>> Dynamic created maps
If you need to build a map dynamically, have a look at this script: [[./data/fantomCX/examples/TileMaps/DynamicMap/DynamicMap.cxs|DynamicMap.cxs]].

>>> Platformer game
To see how you could do collision checks against a Tiled platformer level, have a look at this script: [[./data/fantomCX/examples/TileMaps/Platformer/Platformer.cxs|Platformer.cxs]].

>>> Maps created by Tiled
*Orthographic maps*
For big tile maps, created by the tool Tiled, have a look at the [[./data/fantomCX/examples/TileMaps/Tiled/Tiled.cxs|Tiled.cxs]] script. It even handles map objects now.

*Displaying isometric TILED maps*
To display and use an isometric map which was build in Tiled, study this example script: [[./data/fantomCX/examples/TileMaps/Tiled/TiledIsometric.cxs|TiledIsometric.cxs]].

*Using multiple tile sheets in on map*
If your map uses multiple tile sheets, look at this example: [[./data/fantomCX/examples/TileMaps/Tiled/MultiTileSets.cxs|MultiTileSets.cxs]].

*Using physics within a platformer game*
Sometimes you want to use physics in a platformer game. Study this example: [[./data/fantomCX/examples/TileMaps/Platformer_Physics/Platformer_Physics.cxs|Platformer_Physics.cxs]].

